Basic inferential data analysis. The Effect of Vitamin C on Tooth Growth in Guinea Pigs

October 08, 2016 posts

Basic inferential data analysis. The Effect of Vitamin C on Tooth Growth in Guinea Pigs.

  • Data overview
  • 1. Summary of the data
  • 2. Use confidence intervals and/or hypothesis tests to compare tooth growth by supp and dose
    • Confedence intervals:
    • Hypothesis tests:
  • 3. Conclusions and the assumptions

Data overview

The response is the length of odontoblasts (teeth) in each of 10 guinea pigs at each of three dose levels of Vitamin C (0.5, 1, and 2 mg) with each of two delivery methods (orange juice or ascorbic acid). A data frame with 60 observations on 3 variables: len(Tooth length), supp(Supplement type (VC or OJ)), dose(Dose in milligrams).

data(ToothGrowth)
d <- ToothGrowth

1. Summary of the data

summary(d)
##   lensupp dose  
##  Min.   : 4.20   OJ:30   Min.   :0.500  
##  1st Qu.:13.07   VC:30   1st Qu.:0.500  
##  Median :19.25   Median :1.000  
##  Mean   :18.81   Mean   :1.167  
##  3rd Qu.:25.27   3rd Qu.:2.000  
##  Max.   :33.90   Max.   :2.000

We can point out some data properties:

Property Observations
Supplementary 50% (30 observations) is Orange Juice supplementary
50% (30 observations) is ascorbic acid supplementary
Dose Mean of doze of a supplementary is 1.167 mg
Max doze of a supplementary is 2.000 mg
Min doze of a supplementary is 0.500 mg
Tooth Length Mean of tooth length is 18.81 cm
Max tooth length is 33.90 cm
Min tooth length is 4.20 cm

The following graph is a histogram of the tooth length:

We can say the data is slightly normalized. As the shape is more looks like Gaussian.

The following graph shows the comparison of the tooth length by supplementary type:

  oj_mean <- mean(d[which(d$supp=="OJ"),][,1])
  vc_mean <- mean(d[which(d$supp=="VC"),][,1])
  c(oj_mean, vc_mean)
## [1] 20.66333 16.96333

We can see that OJ has better results as the tooth length mean for this supplementary has more value than VC with the same observation count and dose amounts.

This graph shows that tooth length depends on the dose amount.

2. Use confidence intervals and/or hypothesis tests to compare tooth growth by supp and dose

Confedence intervals:

Firstly, we will group our data by supplementary factor:

x1 <- d[which(d$supp=="VC"),][,1]   #Orange Juice supplementary group values
x2 <- d[which(d$supp=="OJ"),][,1]   #Ascorbic Acid supplementary group values

To calculate the confidence intervals we will use the formula:

mean_x2 - mean_x1 + c(-1,1) * t * sqrt(var_x1/count_x1 + var_x2/count_x2)

Where:

mean_x1 and mean_x2 - mean of each supplementary group

var_x1 and var_x2 - variance of each supplementary group

t - quantile

mean_x1 <- mean(x1)
mean_x2 <- mean(x2)
var_x1  <- sd(x1)^2
var_x2  <- sd(x2)^2

count_x1 <- length(x1)
count_x2 <- length(x2)

q <- (((var_x1 + var_x2)/count_x1)^2) / ((((var_x1/count_x1)^2)+((var_x2/count_x2)^2))/(count_x1-1))
t <- qt(0.975, q)

mean_x2 - mean_x1 + c(-1,1) * t * sqrt(var_x1/count_x1 + var_x2/count_x2)
## [1] -0.1710156  7.5710156

Hypothesis tests:

t.test(len~supp, data=d, paired=FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  len by supp
## t = 1.9153, df = 55.309, p-value = 0.06063
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.1710156  7.5710156
## sample estimates:
## mean in group OJ mean in group VC 
## 20.66333 16.96333

Now we can start to check the hypothesis by splitting the data by dose amount:

y1 <- subset(d, dose==0.5)
y2 <- subset(d, dose==1.0)
y3 <- subset(d, dose==2.0)

And make tests for each dose (0.5, 1.0, 2.0).

t.test(len~supp, data=y1, paired=FALSE)$conf
## [1] 1.719057 8.780943
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95

We can reject the null hypothesis and can conclude that orange juice (OJ) is more effective for this dose level.

t.test(len~supp, data=y2, paired=FALSE)$conf
## [1] 2.802148 9.057852
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95

We can reject the null hypothesis and can conclude that orange juice (OJ) is more effective for this dose level too.

t.test(len~supp, data=y3, paired=FALSE)$conf
## [1] -3.79807  3.63807
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95

Here, we cannot reject the null hypothesis and we cannot conclude that one of the supplementaries is better than the other at the top dose level.

3. Conclusions and the assumptions

As a result we can say that:

  1. Orange Juice showed better results as it was found that the tooth length increases more using this supplementary after reviewing the data means grouped by supplementary and hypothesis tests (via Summary of the data and Hypothesis test part);

  2. On the other hand we can see that higher doses increases the tooth length for both supplementaries which was proved by both: quick data overview and hypothesis tests (via Summary of the data and Hypothesis test part).
